Introduction to the Dataset¶

The dataset consists of four files, each providing different types of information related to retail transactions between December 2021 and December 2023:

  • Transactional Data: There are two files, Transactional_data_retail_01.csv and Transactional_data_retail_02.csv, that contain the details of each sale. These files include the following columns:

    • Invoice: The unique invoice number for each transaction.
    • StockCode: The unique identifier for each product.
    • Quantity: The number of units sold for each product.
    • Price: The price per unit of the product.
    • Customer ID: The identifier for the customer who made the purchase (if available).
    • InvoiceDate: The date of the transaction.

  • Product Information: The file ProductInfo.csv contains descriptions of the products, linked to the transactional data by the StockCode column.

  • Customer Information: The file CustomerDemographics.csv provides demographic details of customers, including the Customer ID and Country, allowing for customer-level analysis.

The primary goal of this analysis is to forecast the demand for the next 15 weeks, focusing on the top 10 best-selling products. The most critical variables for demand forecasting will be the StockCode (which identifies each product) and the Quantity sold over time.

It’s also important to note that there are some missing values in the Customer ID column of the transactional data, which likely represent anonymous or untracked purchases. These rows still contribute to demand forecasting as they provide valid information about the products sold.

Handling Missing Customer IDs in Demand Forecasting¶

Even though the Customer ID is missing imanyme ro of the retail datasetsws, the transactions still happened. The quantity sold, price, and stock code are still valid, and these rows contribute to the overall demand. So, even if we don’t know who bought the product, it’s still important to include these rows.

Should We Keep These Rows?¶

Yes, it's better to keep these rows because they show actual sales. Even without customer information, the quantity sold and the stock code give us valuable insights into what products were sold. This is key for forecasting future dvai

We will convert these missing values to a number llike '99' as an indicator/placeholder that these values are missing. lable.

#Customer Spending
q0 = '''
SELECT c."Customer id", c.Country, SUM(r1.Price * r1.Quantity) AS Revenue_Retail1, SUM(r2.Price * r2.Quantity) AS Revenue_Retail2
FROM customer_s c
JOIN retail1_s r1 ON c."Customer ID" = r1."Customer ID"
JOIN retail2_s r2 ON c."Customer id" = r2."Customer ID"
WHERE r1.Quantity > 0 AND r2.Quantity > 0
GROUP BY c."Customer ID"
ORDER BY Revenue_Retail1 DESC, Revenue_Retail2 DESC
LIMIT 20

'''
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.2f}'.format)
top20spending_customers = pd.read_sql(q0, engine)

#Customer Spending over the Months
q_spending = '''
SELECT c."Customer ID", r.Year, r.Month, SUM(r.Price * r.Quantity) AS Monthly_Spending
FROM customer_s c 
JOIN (
   SELECT "Customer ID", Year, Month, Price, Quantity FROM retail1_s
   UNION ALL
   SELECT "Customer ID", Year, Month, Price, Quantity FROM retail2_s
) r ON c."Customer ID" = r."Customer ID"
WHERE r.Quantity > 0
GROUP BY c."Customer ID", r.Year, r.Month
ORDER BY r.Year, r.Month, c."Customer ID"
'''
#UNION ALL: Combines the data from retail1_s and retail2_s into one dataset.
customer_spending_by_month = pd.read_sql(q_spending, engine)

q_c = '''

JOIN (
    SELECT * FROM retail1_s
    UNION ALL 
    SELECT * FROM retail2_s
) r ON c."Customer ID" = r."Customer ID"
JOIN product_s p ON r.StockCode = p.StockCode
GROUP BY c.Country
ORDER BY Total_Transaction DESC

# Query to get Total Sales by StockCode and country
q1 = '''
SELECT p.Description, r.price, r.StockCode, c.country, SUM(r.Quantity) AS Total_Sold
FROM retail1_s r
JOIN customer_s c ON r."Customer ID" = c."Customer ID"
JOIN product_s p ON r.StockCode = p.StockCode
GROUP by r.StockCode, c.Country
ORDER BY Total_Sold DESC
LIMIT 10;
'''
top10_sales_by_stockcode = pd.read_sql(q1, engine)
top10_sales_by_stockcode

Interpretation:

  • Missing Descriptions: Some products have missing descriptions (marked as No Description Available), but they still account for a significant number of sales.
  • Variety of Prices: The prices of the top-selling products range from £0.85 to £6.75, showing a diversity of products sold at different price points.
  • This information can be used to analyze high-demand products across countries and examine pricing strategies based on the top sellers.

#First combine the datasets, and set InvoieDate as Index of the DataFrame
q_ts = '''
SELECT r.InvoiceDate, r.Invoice, r.StockCode, r.Quantity, r.Price, p.Description, c."Customer ID", c.Country
FROM (
    SELECT "InvoiceDate", "Invoice", "StockCode", "Quantity", "Price", "Customer ID" FROM retail1_s
    UNION ALL
    SELECT "InvoiceDate", "Invoice", "StockCode", "Quantity", "Price", "Customer ID" FROM retail2_s
) r
JOIN customer_s c ON r."Customer ID" = c."Customer ID"
JOIN product_s p ON r.StockCode = p.StockCode
WHERE r.Quantity > 0
ORDER BY r.InvoiceDate;
'''
# Fetch the merged data into a DataFrame
timeseries = pd.read_sql(q_ts, engine)

Time Series on Top 10 Products : ARMA, ARIMA, SARIMA¶

In [223]:
#Code for getting the Test Train split of a Product (based on timePeriod)
def get_train_test(p):
    p=p.set_index('InvoiceDate')
    p.index = pd.to_datetime(p.index)
    # Aggregate the data to remove duplicate dates by summing the quantities
    p = p.groupby(p.index).sum()
    p = p.asfreq('M')
    train, test = p[p.index < pd.to_datetime('2023-07-01')], p[p.index > pd.to_datetime('2023-07-01')]
    train = train.sort_index()
    test = test.sort_index()
    return (train, test)

#Code for ARMA Model
def ARMA_pred(p):
    train, test = get_train_test(p)
    #Aggregate Same values over Train i.e Transactions Over same dates
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()
    y = train['Quantity'] #Could be Revenue also
    ARMA_model = SARIMAX(y, order=(2, 1, 2))
    ARMA_model = ARMA_model.fit()
    y_pred = ARMA_model.get_forecast(len(test.index))
    y_pred_df = y_pred.conf_int(alpha=0.05)
    y_pred_df['Predictions'] = ARMA_model.predict(start=y_pred_df.index[0], end=y_pred_df.index[-1])
    y_pred_df.index = test.index
    y_pred_out = y_pred_df['Predictions']
    return y_pred_out

    
#Code for ARIMA Model
def ARIMA_pred(p):
    train, test = get_train_test(p)
    #Aggregate Same values over Train i.e Transactions Over same dates
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()
    y = train['Quantity'] #Could be Revenue also
    ARIMAmodel = ARIMA(y, order = (2, 1, 1))
    ARIMAmodel = ARIMAmodel.fit()

    y_pred = ARIMAmodel.get_forecast(len(test.index))
    y_pred_df = y_pred.conf_int(alpha = 0.05) 
    y_pred_df["Predictions"] = ARIMAmodel.predict(start = y_pred_df.index[0], end = y_pred_df.index[-1])
    y_pred_df.index = test.index
    y_pred_out = y_pred_df["Predictions"]
    return y_pred_out
#Code for SARIMA Model
def SARIMA_pred(p):
    train, test = get_train_test(p)
    #Aggregate Same values over Train i.e Transactions Over same dates
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    # Make sure your time series is regularly spaced
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()
    y = train['Quantity'] #Could be Revenue also
    SARIMAXmodel = SARIMAX(y, order = (1, 1,1), seasonal_order=(1,1,1,12))
    SARIMAXmodel = SARIMAXmodel.fit()

    y_pred = SARIMAXmodel.get_forecast(len(test.index))
    y_pred_df = y_pred.conf_int(alpha = 0.05) 
    y_pred_df["Predictions"] = SARIMAXmodel.predict(start = y_pred_df.index[0], end = y_pred_df.index[-1])
    y_pred_df.index = test.index
    y_pred_out = y_pred_df["Predictions"] 
    return y_pred_out

from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

# Code for Exponential Smoothing Model
def ETS_pred(p):
    train, test = get_train_test(p)
    
    # Aggregate same values over Train i.e., Transactions over same dates
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()
    
    y = train['Quantity']  # Could be Revenue also
    
    # Fit the Exponential Smoothing model
    ETS_model = ExponentialSmoothing(y, seasonal_periods=12, trend='add')
    ETS_model = ETS_model.fit()
    
    # Forecast for the test set length
    y_pred = ETS_model.forecast(len(test.index))
    
    # Set the predicted values to the test index
    y_pred.index = test.index
    
    return y_pred

def plot_preds_ARMA_ARIMA_SARIMA_ETS(p):
    train, test = get_train_test(p)
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()

    # Plot Train and Test Data 
    sns.set()
    plt.plot(train.index, train['Quantity'], color="black", label="Train Data")
    plt.plot(test.index, test['Quantity'], color="red", label="Test Data")

    # Get ARMA and ARIMA predictions
    ARMA_preds = ARMA_pred(p)
    ARIMA_preds = ARIMA_pred(p)
    SARIMA_preds = SARIMA_pred(p)
    ETS_preds = ETS_pred(p)

    # Plot predictions
    plt.plot(ARMA_preds, color='green', label='ARMA Predictions')
    plt.plot(ARIMA_preds, color='yellow', label='ARIMA Predictions')
    plt.plot(SARIMA_preds, color='blue', label='SARIMA Predictions')
    plt.plot(ETS_preds, color='purple', label='ETS Predictions')
    # Correcting labels and title
    plt.ylabel('Quantity Sold')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title(f"Time Series Models  {p['Description'].iloc[0]} ({p['StockCode'].iloc[0]})")
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def get_rmse(p):
    # Get Train/Test split
    train, test = get_train_test(p)

    # Aggregate Same values over Train and Test if necessary (group by date)
    train = train.groupby(train.index).sum()
    test = test.groupby(test.index).sum()
    
    # ARMA predictions and RMSE
    y_pred_arma = ARMA_pred(p)
    rmse_arma = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test['Quantity'], y_pred_arma))
    print(f"RMSE for product {p['StockCode'].iloc[0]} based on ARMA is: {rmse_arma}")

    # ARIMA predictions and RMSE
    y_pred_arima = ARIMA_pred(p)
    rmse_arima = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test['Quantity'], y_pred_arima))
    print(f"RMSE for product {p['StockCode'].iloc[0]} based on ARIMA is: {rmse_arima}")

    # SARIMA predictions and RMSE (assuming SARIMA_pred is defined)
    y_pred_sarima = SARIMA_pred(p)
    rmse_sarima = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test['Quantity'], y_pred_sarima))
    print(f"RMSE for product {p['StockCode'].iloc[0]} based on SARIMA is: {rmse_sarima}")

    y_pred_ets = ETS_pred(p)
    rmse_ets = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(test['Quantity'], y_pred_ets))
    print(f"RMSE for product {p['StockCode'].iloc[0]} based on ETS is: {rmse_ets}")

    try:
        get_rmse(p_data)
